      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Joint Tenants vs Tenants in Common When Selling Property in Queensland
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Your ownership structure determines who can sign a contract, how proceeds are divided, and what happens when co-owners cannot agree. Know where you stand before you list.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most Queensland property owners who co-own a property with someone else have never looked at how that ownership is actually recorded on title. They know they own it together, but whether they own it as joint tenants or tenants in common is a detail that most owners discover only when they try to sell, when a relationship breaks down, or when one owner dies. By that point, the structure can complicate what should be a straightforward transaction.</p>

      <p>Understanding which structure applies to your property, and what it means for how you can sell, takes about ten minutes and a title search. Getting that clarity before you engage a real estate agent or sign anything is worth the effort.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The core difference: survivorship versus separate shares</h2>
      <p>Joint tenancy means all owners hold the property together as a single legal unit. Each owner has an equal share, and there is a right of survivorship: if one joint tenant dies, their interest automatically passes to the surviving owner or owners regardless of what their will says. The property does not form part of the deceased's estate for distribution purposes. This is the most common structure for married couples buying together, and it was the default structure for many decades in Queensland conveyancing.</p>

      <p>Tenants in common means each owner holds a separate, defined share. Those shares can be equal, 50/50, or unequal, such as 60/40 or 70/30. Each share is distinct and can be dealt with independently. A tenant in common can leave their share to whoever they choose in their will, sell their share, or mortgage their share independently of the other owners (subject to any co-ownership agreement). There is no right of survivorship, when a tenant in common dies, their share passes according to their estate, not automatically to the co-owner.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How your ownership structure affects who can sell</h2>
      <p>For a straightforward sale where all owners agree, the structure makes little practical difference. All owners sign the contract of sale, the settlement is managed by the solicitors, and proceeds are distributed. Whether you hold as joint tenants or tenants in common, the signing requirements are the same, every registered owner must be a party to the contract.</p>

      <p>The structure becomes significant when owners disagree, when one owner has died, or when one owner's circumstances have changed in a way that affects their ability or willingness to proceed with a sale.</p>

      <p>If one joint tenant dies, the surviving tenant simply provides evidence of death to the Queensland titles registry and the title is updated to show them as the sole registered owner. They can then sell without any involvement from the deceased's estate. This is simple and clean, which is why joint tenancy is common for couples.</p>

      <p>If one tenant in common dies, their share passes through their estate. The executor or administrator of that estate must be formally appointed before the share can be dealt with. If probate is required, and it usually is for a property interest, that process takes several months. A sale of the whole property cannot proceed until the estate administration is complete and the new registered owner is confirmed on title.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens when one co-owner wants to sell and the other does not</h2>
      <p>This is the situation that causes the most difficulty, and it arises more often than most people expect: relationship breakdown between couples, disputes between siblings who inherited together, disagreements between investment partners about timing.</p>

      <p>Joint tenants cannot be forced to sell without legal process, but a joint tenant who wants out has an option that tenants in common do not. A joint tenancy can be severed unilaterally, one owner can convert their share into a tenants-in-common interest without the other owner's agreement, simply by registering a notice with the titles registry. Once severed, each former joint tenant holds a 50% tenants-in-common share. Neither can then force a sale on the other, but each can deal with their half independently.</p>

      <p>For tenants in common, each owner can also sell their own share independently, but finding a buyer for a half share in a property is extremely difficult in practice, and most buyers are not interested in co-owning a property with a stranger. In both scenarios, if the co-owners cannot reach agreement on selling, the available legal remedy in Queensland is a partition application to the Supreme Court. The court can order the property to be sold and proceeds distributed. This is slow, expensive, and almost always less desirable than a negotiated outcome, but it is the backstop that exists when all else fails.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Tenants in common with unequal shares: how proceeds are split</h2>
      <p>When tenants in common hold unequal shares, the sale proceeds are distributed according to the registered proportions after deducting the costs of sale. If one owner holds a 60% interest and the other holds 40%, they receive 60 cents and 40 cents of every net dollar respectively. The proportions are recorded on title and govern the distribution, there is no room for informal arrangements unless they are documented in a separate co-ownership agreement executed by all parties.</p>

      <p>Unequal shares commonly arise with investment partners who contributed different amounts to the purchase, or where one party received a larger inheritance share. They also arise in family situations where parents transfer partial ownership to adult children for estate planning purposes. If your shares are unequal, confirm the registered proportions on title before listing, the figure on the current title search is the legally operative one, not any informal understanding between the parties.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to check which structure applies to your property</h2>
      <p>A Queensland title search will show you the registered owners and whether they hold as joint tenants or tenants in common. You can order a current title search from the Queensland titles registry online for a small fee, or your solicitor can obtain one as part of the pre-sale process. The wording on title is clear: it will either note "joint tenants" or specify each owner's share as a fraction, indicating tenants in common.</p>

      <p>If you are unsure what was registered at the time of purchase, or if the structure may have changed since (for example, following a death or a deliberate severance of joint tenancy), your solicitor can confirm the current position from the register.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common scenarios: couples, siblings, investment partners</h2>
      <p>Married couples who bought together before around 2000 are most likely to hold as joint tenants, it was the default structure and was rarely explained at the time. Most have no intention of ever owning separately or directing their share elsewhere via a will, so joint tenancy suits them fine. Couples in blended families or second marriages, where the interest of biological children from a previous relationship needs to be protected, sometimes change to tenants in common to ensure their share passes to their chosen beneficiaries rather than automatically to the surviving spouse.</p>

      <p>Siblings who inherit together through a deceased estate almost always hold as tenants in common, in equal or specified shares as set out in the will or distribution. Selling an inherited property between siblings requires all registered owners or their legal representatives to agree and sign. Where one sibling is an overseas resident or is otherwise difficult to reach, obtaining signatures can add delay to a sale.</p>

      <p>Investment partners, whether friends, colleagues, or family members who bought together, typically hold as tenants in common with shares reflecting their financial contribution. A co-ownership agreement prepared at the time of purchase should set out the process for a sale, how a deadlock is resolved, and what happens if one partner wants to exit. If no agreement exists, the default is that both parties must agree to sell, and disputes fall back to the court process described above.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The solicitor's role before and during a co-owned sale</h2>
      <p>Your solicitor's role in a co-owned sale goes beyond the standard conveyancing. They confirm the registered ownership structure, ensure all parties are correctly identified and have capacity to sign, manage any issues arising from deceased estates or changed circumstances, and prepare the transfer documents in a form that the titles registry will accept. Where there is any co-owner tension, they can also advise on the legal options available without having to go to court.</p>

      <p>Engaging a solicitor before you list, not just to review the contract after it is signed, gives you the opportunity to identify any title issues early and resolve them before they cause delay in a live sale campaign. A title defect or missing co-owner consent discovered after a buyer has signed and paid a deposit is a significantly worse position than discovering it at the preparation stage.</p>

